fore 1340":"vóór 1340","about 1355":"circa 1355","1319":"1319","1417":"1417","1406":"1406","England":"England","of Cavendish Overhall, Suffolk, England ":"Cavendish, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devendish, Overhall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","Cavendish, Suffolk, England":"Cavendish, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"before 1340–15 June 1381":"before 1340–15 June 1381","1340–1381":"1340–1381","1330–1381":"1330–1381","1358–1396":"1358–1396","1374–1406":"1374–1406","1374–1417":"1374–1417","1320–Male":"1320–Deceased","1319–Female":"1319–Deceased","15 June 1381":"15 June 1381","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1381":"1381","1358":"1358","about 1358":"about 1358","1320":"1320","before 1340":"before 1340","about 1355":"about 1355","1319":"1319","1417":"1417","1406":"1406","England":"England","of Cavendish Overhall, Suffolk, England ":"Cavendish, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Devendish, Overhall, Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England":"Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England","Cavendish, Suffolk, England":"Cavendish, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cavendish","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Suffolk named Cavendish, from an Old English byname <i>Cāfna</i> (meaning ‘bold, daring’) + Old English <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosed pasture’. <i>Cavendish</i> is the surname of the Dukes of Devonshire. They are descended from Sir John Cavendish, who served as Chief Justice of the King's Bench (1372–81). Under the Tudors and Stuarts, a succession of shrewd and powerful heads of the family achieved political prominence and became extremely wealthy. William Cavendish, 2nd Earl of Devonshire, was a strong supporter of the ‘Glorious Revolution’ of 1688 and of William of Orange (William III) against James II. In 1694 he was created Duke of Devonshire. The Latin family motto, <i>Cavendo tutus</i> ‘safe through taking care’ is a pun on the surname.","Manx: Anglicized form of <i>Corjeag</i>, a shortened form of <i>Mac Quartag</i> ‘son of <i>Svarteygr</i>’ (from Old Norse, meaning ‘black-eyed’). Folk etymology interpreted <i>Corjeag</i> incorrectly as Manx <i>curjeig</i> ‘alms-dish’ and equally incorrectly supposed that the surname <i>Cavendish</i> was a synonym meaning ‘giving-dish’. Manxmen's familiarity with the English surname presumably led to the substitution."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Cavendish was born before 1340, in Cavendish, Suffolk, England, his father, Robert de Gernon of Grimston Hall, was 19 and his mother, Mary Potton or Potkin, was 20. He married Alice de Odyngseles about 1355, in Cavendish, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. In 1372, his occupation is listed as chief justice of the king's bench in England. He died on 15 June 1381, in his hometown, and was buried in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"before 1340–15 June 1381":"enne 1340–15. juuni 1381","1340–1381":"1340–1381","1330–1381":"1330–1381","1358–1396":"1358–1396","1374–1406":"1374–1406","1374–1417":"1374–1417","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1319–Female":"1319–Surnud","15 June 1381":"15. juuni 1381","1374":"1374","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","1381":"1381","1358":"1358","about 1358":"umbes 1358","1320":"1320","before 1340":"enne 1340","about 1355":"umbes 1355","1319":"1319","1417":"1417","1406":"1406","England":"England","of Cavendish Overhall, Suffolk, England ":"Cavendish, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devendish, Overhall, Suffolk, Engla